Since \( (A \cup B) \cup (A \cup B') = \Omega \) (the entire sample space), \( P((A \cup B) \cup (A \cup B')) = 1 \). Also, \( (A \cup B) \cap (A \cup B') = A \), so \( P((A \cup B) \cap (A \cup B')) = P(A) \). Substituting the values:  

\[ 1 = 0.76 + 0.87 - P(A) \]  
\[ 1 = 1.63 - P(A) \]  
\[ P(A) = 1.63 - 1 = 0.63 \]  

The result is a numeric value with two significant figures, consistent with the input data.  

