Problem:  Of a group of patients having injuries, $28 \%$ visit both a physical therapist and a chiropractor and $8 \%$ visit neither. Say that the probability of visiting a physical therapist exceeds the probability of visiting a chiropractor by $16 \%$. What is the probability of a randomly selected person from this group visiting a physical therapist?
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The probability of visiting a physical therapist is found using the given information and probability principles. Let \( P(P) \) be the probability of visiting a physical therapist and \( P(C) \) be the probability of visiting a chiropractor.

Given:
- \( P(P \text{ and } C) = 0.28 \)
- \( P(\text{neither}) = 0.08 \)
- \( P(P) = P(C) + 0.16 \)

The probability of visiting at least one is:
\[
P(P \text{ or } C) = 1 - P(\text{neither}) = 1 - 0.08 = 0.92
\]

Using the inclusion-exclusion principle:
\[
P(P \text{ or } C) = P(P) + P(C) - P(P \text{ and } C)
\]
\[
0.92 = P(P) + P(C) - 0.28
\]
\[
P(P) + P(C) = 0.92 + 0.28 = 1.20
\]

Substitute \( P(P) = P(C) + 0.16 \):
\[
(P(C) + 0.16) + P(C) = 1.20
\]
\[
2P(C) + 0.16 = 1.20
\]
\[
2P(C) = 1.20 - 0.16 = 1.04
