- The \(^1D\) term has a degeneracy of \((2 \times 0 + 1) \times (2 \times 2 + 1) = 1 \times 5 = 5\).
- The \(^1S\) term has a degeneracy of \((2 \times 0 + 1) \times (2 \times 0 + 1) = 1 \times 1 = 1\).

Summing these gives the total number of states: \(9 + 5 + 1 = 15\).

Alternatively, combinatorially, the number of ways to place two indistinguishable electrons in six possible spin-orbital states (3 orbitals × 2 spins) while adhering to the Pauli exclusion principle is \(\binom{6}{2} = 15\).

